Vegas odds highest on Nomadland. Moved Mank higher than vegas because the academy historically votes for films about the industry. Minari skewed up due to the cultural phenomenon it’s become (a potential Parasite or Moonlight situation).

There seem to be no eclectic-type films on the roster (my opinion, of course), and bio/historical dramas have the edge on other categories (over past 30 years). Also, more often than not, over last thirty years, films win that Golden Globe best picture lose the Oscars best picture more than half of the time. Wisdom of the crowd says Nomadland, though.

Primero, considerando que nunca en las más de 90 premiaciones ha habido un empate en esta categoría, la última opción la descarté. Busqué el número de nominaciones que han tenido en la misma categoría pero en distintas premiaciones, siendo (6, 3, 4, 11, 24, 10, 11, 10) Busqué también el número de nominaciones que tienen en otras categorías de los Óscar (5, 5, 9, 5, 5, 4, 5, 5) También busqué la puntuación asignada a cada película por parte de RottenTomatoes e IMBd (98% + 8,3/10 ; 96% + 7,6/10 ; 83% + 7/10 ; 98% + 7,6/10 ; 94% + 7,5/10 ; 90% + 7,5/10 ; 97% + 7,8/10 ; 89% + 7,8/10) Finalmente, en base a esta información es que pude armar mis predicciones, con Nomadland en la delantera. Cabe destacar que esta película ganó la versión del 2020 del Toronto Film Festival, el cual históricamente se lo han ganado muchos ganadores del Óscar de Mejor Película.

Para hacer esta predicción me basé en los siguientes datos: - Recepción por parte de la crítica -Número de nominaciones totales en los Oscar -Número de nominaciones totales (contando varias premiaciones) -Premios ganados en otras premiaciones (tanto el número como la categoría)

Updated to increase odds for Minari, Nomadland, and Promising Young Woman - the top three frontrunners being nominated across film festivals in America. This means a slight decrease for The Trial of the Chicago 7.
Nomadland is lacking a Writer's Guild nomination and The Father did not make AFI or NBR list. Adjusted for these reasons.

The Trial of the Chicago 7, compared to the other nominees, fits many statistical indicators of winners (ensemble, PGA, DGA, SAG, editing nom, etc., running time, release date, etc.). My main doubts about this movie is that it resides in a competitive Best Picture category, was released on Netflix, has a strong political tones and harsh cut-aways, did not get a Directing nomination, and did not premiere at a major film festival like Cannes, Venice, Toronto, Sundance, TIFF, Telluride, Tribeca, etc. which most Best Picture winners achieve. It currently stands #2 on Gold Derby, which in almost all cases the #1 pick loses to the #2 pick in recent years. One Night in Miami and Ma Rainey's Black Bottom were both snubbed, which are both throwback historical films in a way and this may be a sign that Trial of the Chicago 7 may meet the same fate as the two snubs mentioned.

From what I've been following, the 3 front runners are Judas, Minari, and Nomadland. Mank and Chicago 7 will have a lot of buzz, but the influx of new, young, diverse members leads me to believe that the rank choice voting will have tighter groupings of the more diverse films at the top.
